        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2517249184" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17966850227466183616">The Collected Stories of Eudora Welty won the 1982 National Book Award. There are forty-two short stories in this lengthy 622 page book. I enjoyed the earlier stories in the book but not many of the later ones. Weltyâs stories feel quite dated reading some seventy years later. Here are some of the ones I liked. <br/><br/>1. Why I Live at the Post Office. Sister alienates family by making too many assumptions but is able to get the family on her side by telling blatant lies and manipulating others.<br/>2. Old M</span>
  <span id="freeText17966850227466183616" style="display:none">The Collected Stories of Eudora Welty won the 1982 National Book Award. There are forty-two short stories in this lengthy 622 page book. I enjoyed the earlier stories in the book but not many of the later ones. Weltyâs stories feel quite dated reading some seventy years later. Here are some of the ones I liked. <br /><br />1. Why I Live at the Post Office. Sister alienates family by making too many assumptions but is able to get the family on her side by telling blatant lies and manipulating others.<br />2. Old Mr Marblehall. He lives a double life with a son by each wife. The sons even look alike. The author dreams of how one day Marblehallâs secret will be exposed. Maybe one of his young sons will follow their dad to the other house.<br />3. Flowers for Marjorie. Creepy story. Man kills pregnant wife.<br />4. The Wide Net. Husband thinks young pregnant wife has drowned herself. He spends all day dragging the river to find her body. She was just hiding the whole time seeking attention.<br />5. Livvie. Husband is old and sickly and dying. Livvie brings a young man home who is her age. They watch the old man die and begin dancing<br /><br />3.5 stars. I didnât love these stories as much as I anticipated since I previously read Weltyâs novel called The Optimistâs Daughter and enjoyed it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17966850227466183616" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
