<div id="review_2428210319" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2428210319" />
    <a title="Mackey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28470777-mackey"><img alt="Mackey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1635008931p2/28470777.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2428210319?book_show_action=true">Jun 18, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mackey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mackey" href="/user/show/28470777-mackey">Mackey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/28470777-mackey?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/28470777-mackey?shelf=southern-lit">southern-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/28470777-mackey?shelf=my-reviews">my-reviews</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/28470777-mackey?shelf=books-read-2018">books-read-2018</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2428210319" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13869309266193638561">Eudora Welty is the epitome of the Southern Female Writer. She and Flannery O&apos;Connor brought a realism to southern literature that few of their male counterparts ever mastered. Through their writing, readers all over the world captured a glimpse of the poor, the struggling, the different, the proud, the hard-working, the true Southerner that other writers only envisioned in their imaginations. Gone was the verbosity of Faulkner and replaced in its stead the stark reality of what it was to be a &quot;</span>
  <span id="freeText13869309266193638561" style="display:none">Eudora Welty is the epitome of the Southern Female Writer. She and Flannery O'Connor brought a realism to southern literature that few of their male counterparts ever mastered. Through their writing, readers all over the world captured a glimpse of the poor, the struggling, the different, the proud, the hard-working, the true Southerner that other writers only envisioned in their imaginations. Gone was the verbosity of Faulkner and replaced in its stead the stark reality of what it was to be a "southerner." In her short story,<i>"The Worn Path,"</i> a simple tale of an elderly Mississippi woman, Welty encapsulated a wealth of imagery and symbolism that still is the topic of debate for students, writers and philosophers world wide. Once, when I was a young university student, I had the honor of meeting Welty and being awarded a literary prize for my paper on her work, <i>The Worn Path.</i> She was and will remain one of America's finest writers. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13869309266193638561" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


